# Issue #528 retake: the previous version of this fixture documented
# row "subtyping" — declaring `say : Unit / Io` (alias for
# `Console + Stdin + Env + File`) when only `Console` was actually
# performed. With #528's full transitive propagation that pattern
# became unsafe: every caller of `say` would inherit the full `Io`
# row even though `Io`'s extra labels (Stdin/Env/File) never get
# touched at runtime. The new discipline is that a function's row
# must reflect what its body actually performs — honest rows, no
# over-declaration.
#
# `say` only calls `print`, so its honest row is `/ Console` (which
# expands to `Stdout + Stderr + Stdin` per the auto-injected alias).
# `main` calls `say`, inherits `Console`, declares `/ Console`. No
# more subtyping illusion to test here; the test is now that the
# honest cascade compiles cleanly.

fn say(s: String) : Unit / Console = print(s)

fn main() : Unit / Console {
  say("subtyping works")
  ()
}
